### C# Feature Support for Conversion

Most C# features convert cleanly to Calor. Key supported features include:

**Fully supported**: classes, structs, interfaces, enums, records, abstract/sealed/static classes, generics (including nested), inheritance, properties (auto/computed/init), fields, constructors (with base/this chains), methods (virtual/override/abstract/async), operators (including implicit/explicit conversion), indexers, events, delegates, lambdas, LINQ, pattern matching (type/constant/relational/logical and/or/not/var/discard/tuple/positional patterns), switch expressions, nullable types, string interpolation, collection expressions, goto/label, yield return/break, throw expressions, lock, stackalloc, volatile, extension methods, using declarations, with expressions, required members.

**Partial support** (most usage converts): is-pattern with complex recursion, implicit `new()` with arguments, checked/unchecked blocks (wrapper stripped, body preserved).

**Not yet supported**: list/slice patterns (`[a, ..rest]`), `ref struct`, `static abstract` interface members, `in` parameters, mixed collection spread (`[1, ..other]`).

Use `calor_help` with action=features to check specific features, or `calor_batch` with action=analyze to assess an entire project.

### Quick Syntax Reference

Calor is **indent-only**: a block's body is indented under its opener and ends at
the next dedent. There are **no closing tags** — never write `§/`-prefixed closers.

| Structure | Calor Syntax |
|-----------|-------------|
| Module | `§M{id:Name}` (body indented) |
| Function | `§F{id:name:vis} (type:name, ...) -> retType` (body indented) |
| Binding | `§B{name} expr` (immutable), `§B{~name} expr` (mutable) |
| Loop | `§L{id:var:from:to:step}` (body indented) |
| Conditional | `§IF{id} (cond)` + `§EI (cond)` / `§EL`; inline `§IF{id} (cond) → §R expr` |
| Contracts | `§Q (precondition)`, `§S (postcondition)` |
| Types | `i32`, `i64`, `str`, `bool`, `f64`, `void`, `?i32` (option), `i32!str` (result) |
| Expressions | Prefix notation: `(+ a b)`, `(== x 0)`, `(% i 15)` |
| Literals | `INT:42`, `STR:"hello"`, `BOOL:true`, `FLOAT:3.14` |

### Exemplar idioms (E1a-hardened)

The idioms agents most often get wrong. Copy these shapes verbatim.

**Calls** — every argument is prefixed with `§A`; the argument list closes with `§/C`:

```
§B{lines:[str]} §C{File.ReadAllLines} §A path §/C
§C{File.AppendAllText} §A path §A (+ key (+ "=" (+ value "\n"))) §/C
§B{ok:bool} §C{File.Exists} §A path §/C
§B{n:i32} §C{LocalFunc} §A x §/C
```

**Strings are prefix ops, not method calls:**

```
(len s)              s.Length            (substr s start count)   s.Substring
(contains s sub)     s.Contains          (starts s pre)           s.StartsWith
(replace s old new)  s.Replace           (trim s)  (upper s)  (lower s)
§B{c:str} (substr line i 1)      // single char at index i, as a str
```

**Lists and dictionaries** (empty literals close with `§/LIST` / `§/DICT`):

```
§LIST{items:str}
§/LIST{items}
§PUSH{items} x               items.Add(x)      [needs mut effect]
§B{n:i32} §CNT{items}        items.Count
§B{e:str} §IDX items i       items[i]
§DICT{ages:str:i32}
§/DICT{ages}
§PUT{ages} k v               ages[k] = v       [needs mut effect]
```

**Effects:** a function whose body mutates a collection (`§PUSH`, `§PUT`, `§SETIDX`)
must declare `mut` in `§E{...}`; file reads/writes need `fs:r` / `fs:w` / `fs:rw`.
Callers must declare at least the union of their callees' effects.

**Arrays vs lists (measured trap):** `File.ReadAllLines` returns an ARRAY — bind it
as `[str]`. Do NOT copy `[str]` into a signature that requires `List<str>`; match the
type the surrounding surface declares.

